properties.description: International trade classifications cover only dog and cat food. FAO trade data also cover food for other pets (i.e. fish, birds, etc.), whenever possible.

properties.label: Pigeon peas
properties.description: Pigeon pea, cajan pea, Congo bean (Cajanus cajan).

properties.label: Pigeons, other birds
properties.description: Including inter alia: partridge (Alectoris rufa); pigeon (Columba livia); quail (Coturnis spp.); turtle dove, pheasant, etc.. See 1057.

properties.label: Pigs
properties.description: Domestic pig (Sus domestica); wild boar (Sus scrofa). See 866. Excludes non-domesticated wild boars.

properties.label: Pineapples
properties.description: Ananas comosus; A. sativ. Trade figures may include dried pineapples.

properties.label: Pineapples canned
properties.description: Fruit pulp prepared in water, syrup, etc.

properties.label: Pistachios
properties.description: Pistacia vera. Produced mainly in the Near East and the United States.

properties.label: Plantains
properties.description: Musa paradisiaca. Generally known as a cooking banana. Data should be reported excluding the weight of the central stalk

properties.label: Plums and sloes
properties.description: Greengage, mirabelle, damson (Prunus domestica); sloe (P. spinosa).

properties.label: Plums dried (prunes)
properties.description: See 527. Known as prunes.

properties.label: Popcorn
properties.description: Zea mays var. everta. A variety of maize that is eaten after the kernels have been heated and have "popped".

properties.label: Poppy seed
properties.description: Papaver somniferum. The source of opium, poppy seeds are also used in baking and confectionery.

properties.label: Potato offals
properties.description: The residue and waste from the preparation of potatoes.

properties.label: Potatoes
properties.description: Solanum tuberosum Irish potato. A seasonal crop grown in temperate zones all over the world, but primarily in the northern hemisphere.

properties.label: Potatoes, frozen
properties.description: Peeled potatoes that are either cooked or uncooked, sliced or unsliced, and then frozen.

properties.label: Pulses, nes
properties.description: Including inter alia: lablab or hyacinth bean (Dolichos spp.); jack or sword bean (Canavalia spp.); winged bean (Psophocarpus tetragonolobus); guar bean (Cyamopsis tetragonoloba); velvet bean (Stizolobium spp.); yam bean (Pachyrrhizus erosus);. Vigna spp. other than those included in 176 and 195 Other pulses that are not identified separately because of their minor relevance at the international level. Because of their limited local importance, some countries report pulses under this heading that are classified individually by FAO.

properties.label: Pumpkins for Fodder
properties.description: Cucurbita spp. Especially cultivated for fodder..

properties.label: Pumpkins, squash and gourds
properties.description: Cucurbita spp. Includes marrows.

properties.label: Pyrethrum, dried
properties.description: Chrysanthemum cinerariifolium. Includes leaves, stems and flowers. For insecticides, fungicides and similar products.

properties.label: Pyrethrum, extraction
properties.description: Obtained from the flowers by extraction using an organic solvent.

properties.label: Pyrethrum, marc
properties.description: The waste from pyrethrum processing.

properties.label: Quinces
properties.description: Cydonia oblonga; C. vulgaris; C. japonica.

properties.label: Quinoa
properties.description: Chenopodium quinoa (Chenopodiaceae). A minor cereal, which tolerates high altitudes, quinoa is cultivated primarily in andean countries. Used for food and to make chicha, a fermented beverage.

properties.label: Rabbits and hares
properties.description: Oryctolagus cuniculus. See 866. May include domesticated hares (Lepus spp.). Data are expressed in thousands.

properties.label: Raisins
properties.description: Dried grapes. Includes sultanas and currants.

properties.label: Ramie
properties.description: China grass, white ramie (Boehmeria nivea); rhea, green ramie (B. tenacissima). Ramie fibre is obtained from the bast of the plant. For trade coverage see 780

properties.label: Rapeseed
properties.description: Brassica napus var. oleifera. Valued mainly for its oil. Older varieties are rich in Erucic acid, which is considered unhealthy.

properties.label: Raspberries
properties.description: Ubus idaeus. Trade data may include blackberries, mulberries and loganberries (a cross between the raspberry and blackberry).

properties.label: Resins, other
properties.description: Including inter alia: copaiba, copal (Copaifera spp.); gum tragacanth (some Astragalus spp.); incense (Boswellia spp.); myrrh, opopanax, Mecca balsam (Commiphora spp.); tolu balsam, peru balsam (Myroxilon balsamum; M. Pereira). Including lac (resinous substance produced by an insect on several kinds of tropical trees), gums, gum-resins and balsams (vegetable secretions which may solidify on contact with air).

properties.label: Rice, broken
properties.description: Residues from the selection of whole-grain, milled rice.

properties.label: Rice, husked
properties.description: Rice grain without hulls or husks. Also known as brown or cargo rice.

properties.label: Rice, milled
properties.description: White rice milled from locally grown paddy. Includes semi-milled, whole-milled and parboiled rice.

properties.label: Rice, milled/husked
properties.description: White rice milled from imported husked rice. Includes semi-milled, whole-milled and parboiled rice.

properties.label: Rice, paddy
properties.description: Oryza spp., mainly oryza sativa. Rice grain after threshing and winnowing. Also known as rice in the husk and rough rice. Used mainly for human food.

properties.label: Rodents, other
properties.description: See 866. Includes only those used mainly for meat, e.g. Guinea pig. Rodents used mainly for fur skins are included in Code 1169. Data are expressed in thousands.

properties.label: Roots and tubers dried
properties.description: Other tubers, roots or rizhomes, dried, o/t potatoes and cassava.

properties.label: Roots and tubers, nes
properties.description: Including inter alia: arracacha (Arracacoa xanthorrhiza); arrowroot (Maranta arundinacea); chufa (Cyperus esculentus); sago palm (Metroxylon spp.); oca and ullucu (Oxalis tuberosa and Ullucus tuberosus); yam bean, jicama (Pachyrxhizus erosus, P. angulatus); mashua (Tropaeolum tuberosum); Jerusalem artichoke, topinambur (Helianthus tuberosus). Other tubers, roots or rhizomes, fresh, that are not identified separately because of their minor relevance at the international level. Because of their limited local importance, some countries report roots and tubers under this commodity heading that are classified individually by FAO.

properties.label: Rubber natural dry
properties.description: In the form of sheets, crËpes, re-agglomerated granules, free-flowing powders, etc.; includes technically specified natural rubber (TSNR).

properties.label: Rubber, natural
properties.description: Hevea brasiliensis Latex. The liquid secreted by the rubber tree. Includes stabilized or concentrated latex and prevulcanized rubber latex. In trade figures, liquid weight is converted to dry weight at 60%.

properties.label: Rye
properties.description: Secale cereale. A grain that is tolerant of poor soils, high latitudes and altitudes. Mainly used in making bread, whisky and beer. When fed to livestock, it is generally mixed with other grains.

properties.label: Safflower seed
properties.description: Carthamus tinctorius. Valued mainly for its oil. Minor uses include as a human food and as poultry feed.

properties.label: Seed cotton
properties.description: Gossypium spp.: Unginned cotton. Grown for both seed and for fibre. FAO considers cottonseed, cotton lint and linters to be primary products. Lint content ranges from 30 to 40%, seed 55 to 65%, and linters 2 to 5% though they are not always separated.

properties.label: Seeds for planting
properties.description: Seeds, fruits and spores used for sowing. Excludes cereals, oilseeds, pulses and spices, even if intended for sowing.

properties.label: Sesame seed
properties.description: Sesamum indicum. Valued for its oil, but also as a food, either raw or roasted, as well as in bakery products and other food preparations.

properties.label: Sheep
properties.description: Ovis spp.. See 866. Includes Uriel, Argali, Bighorn, Karakul and Astrakhan.

properties.label: Silk raw
properties.description: Obtained by reeling the filaments from cocoons. Not thrown.

properties.label: Silk-worm cocoons, reelable
properties.description: Silkworm cocoons suitable for reeling. Foreign trade data are expressed in silk equivalent, which is 25% of their weight.

properties.label: Sisal
properties.description: Agave sisalana. Sisal fibre is obtained from the leaves of the plant. It also is used as an ornamental plant. Trade data cover fibres that are raw, prepared for spinning, and tow and waste, including yarn waste and garnetted stock.

properties.label: Skins, calve, dry salted
properties.description: See 921.

properties.label: Skins, calve, fresh
properties.description: See 919. From young bovine animals.

properties.label: Skins, calve, nes
properties.description: See 922.

properties.label: Skins, calve, wet salted
properties.description: See 920.

properties.label: Skins, furs
properties.description: High-value raw skins, e.g. mink, fox, beaver.

properties.label: Skins, goat, dry salted
properties.description: Includes kids. See 921.

properties.label: Skins, goat, fresh
properties.description: See 919. Both adult and young animals.

properties.label: Skins, goat, nes
properties.description: Includes kids. See 922.

properties.label: Skins, goat, wet salted
properties.description: Includes kids. See 920.

properties.label: Skins, karakul
properties.description: Raw skins of Astrakhan, Caracul, Persian or similar lambs.

properties.label: Skins, pig, dry salted
properties.description: See 921.

properties.label: Skins, pig, fresh
properties.description: See 919. In many countries, pigskins are not removed from the carcasses.

properties.label: Skins, pig, nes
properties.description: See 922.

properties.label: Skins, pig, wet salted
properties.description: See 920.

properties.label: Skins, rabbit
properties.description: See 919. Both adult and young animals. Trade data include processed skins, including angora.

properties.label: Skins, sheep, dry salted
properties.description: Sheep and lamb skins without wool. See 921.

properties.label: Skins, sheep, fresh
properties.description: See 919. Both adult and young animals.

properties.label: Skins, sheep, nes
properties.description: Sheep and lamb skins without wool. See 922.

properties.label: Skins, sheep, wet salted
properties.description: Sheep and lamb skins without wool. See 920.

properties.label: Skins, sheep, with wool
properties.description: Sheep and lamb skins (excluding 1002), with wool on, salted, dried, limed, pickled or otherwise preserved.

properties.label: Snails, not sea
properties.description: Fresh, chilled, frozen, dried, salted or in brine.

properties.label: Sorghum
properties.description: Sorghum spp.: guinea corn (S. guineense); common, milo, feterita, kaffir corn (S. vulgare); durra, jowar, kaoliang (S. dura). A cereal that has both food and feed uses. Sorghum is a major food grain in most of Africa, where it is also used in traditional beer brewing. It is desirable to report hybrid and other varieties separately.

properties.label: Soya curd
properties.description: Obtained by precipitating proteins from soya milk and removing the fluid. Can be fermented or non-fermented.

properties.label: Soya paste
properties.description: A fermented, salty condiment. Soya paste can be produced through brine fermentation of low- moisture soya curd.

properties.label: Soya sauce
properties.description: A fermented soya product from defatted soybeand and wheat or other cereals that is filtered and pasteurized.

properties.label: Soybeans
properties.description: Glycine soja. The most important oil crop. Also widely consumed as a bean and in the form of various derived products because of its high protein content, e.g. soya milk, meat, etc.

properties.label: Spermaceti
properties.description: Waxy substance extracted from the fat of sperm whales and similar cetaceans.

properties.label: Spices, nes
properties.description: Including inter alia: bay leaves (Laurus nobilis); dill seed (Anethum graveolens); fenugreek seed (Trigonella foenum-graecum); saffron (Crocus sativus); thyme (Thymus vulgaris); turmeric (Curcuma longa). Other spices that are not identified separately because of their minor relevance at the international level. Because of their limited local importance, some countries report spices under this heading that are classified individually by FAO. This heading also includes curry powder and other mixtures of different spices.

properties.label: Spinach
properties.description: Spinacia oleracea. Trade figures may include New Zealand spinach (Tetragonia espansa) and orache (garden) spinach (Atriplex hortensis).

properties.label: Starch, cassava
properties.description: See 119. The principal industrial outlet for cassava. Cassava starch is used in the foodstuffs, textile and paper industries for the manufacture of plywood and veneer, adhesives, glucose and dextrine.

properties.label: Starch, maize
properties.description: See 23. The primary product of the large- scale industrial wet-milling process. Used mainly for the production of glucose, dextrin and alcohol.

properties.label: Starch, potatoes
properties.description: A carbohydrate found in many plant cells. A white odourless powder that is insoluble in cold water, but forms a paste in hot water. Has wide food and non-food uses.

properties.label: Starch, rice
properties.description: See 23 Rice starch is usually obtained from broken rice. Use primarily in the photographic industry to prepare "matt" paper.

properties.label: Starch, wheat
properties.description: Starch is the carbohydrate component in many plant cells. A white, odourless powder that is insoluble in cold water, it forms a paste in hot water. Wheat starch is used for human consumption and animal feed, and is processed into glucose and dextrine for industrial use. It is usually obtained from low-quality flour.

properties.label: Straw husks
properties.description: Cereal straw and husks, unprepared, whether or not chopped, ground, pressed, or in the form of pellets.

properties.label: Strawberries
properties.description: Fragaria spp..

properties.label: String beans
properties.description: Phaseolus vulgaris; Vigna spp. Not for shelling

properties.label: Sugar Raw Centrifugal
properties.description: The sum of codes 158 and 159. Processed further to obtain refined sugar.

properties.label: Sugar beet
properties.description: Beta vulgaris var. altissima. In some producing countries, marginal quantities are consumed, either directly as food or in the preparation of jams.

properties.label: Sugar cane
properties.description: Saccharum officinarum. In some producing countries, marginal quantities of sugar cane are consumed, either directly as food or in the form of juice.

properties.label: Sugar confectionery
properties.description: Sugar confectionery, including chewing gum, that does not contain cocoa. Includes white chocolate.

properties.label: Sugar crops, nes
properties.description: Including inter alia: sugar maple (Acer saccharum); sweet sorghum (Sorghum saccharatum); sugar palm (Arenga saccharifera). Includes minor sugar crops of local importance. In the case of saps, production is to be expressed in liquid equivalent.

properties.label: Sugar non-centrifugal
properties.description: Generally derived from sugar cane through traditional methods without centrifugation.

properties.label: Sugar refined
properties.description: Production covers domestic production, plus or minus imports and/or exports of raw centrifugal sugar in terms of refined sugar.

properties.label: Sugar, beet, raw, centrifugal
properties.description: A non-refined, crystallized material derived from the juices extracted from the root of the sugar beet and consisting either wholly or essentially of sucrose.

properties.label: Sugar, cane, raw, centrifugal
properties.description: A non-refined, crystallized material derived from the juices of sugar-cane stalk and consisting either wholly or essentially of sucrose.

properties.label: Sugar, nes
properties.description: Includes invert sugar, caramel, golden syrup, artificial honey, maltose other than chemically pure, sorghum and palm sugars. See also the general note in the introduction.

properties.label: Sunflower seed
properties.description: Helianthus annuus. Valued mainly for its oil. Minor uses include as a human food and as feed for birds.

properties.label: Swedes for fodder
properties.description: Rutabaga, swede, swede turnip (Brassica napus var napobrassica). Especially cultivated for fodder.

properties.label: Sweet corn frozen
properties.description: Either uncooked, or cooked by steaming or boiling in water, and then frozen.

properties.label: Sweet corn prep or preserved
properties.description: Prepared or preserved other than by vinegar or acetic acid; not frozen.

properties.label: Sweet potatoes
properties.description: Ipomoea batatas. A seasonal crop grown in tropical and subtropical regions. Used mainly for human food. Trade data cover fresh and dried tubers, whether or not sliced or in the form or pellets.

properties.label: Tallow
properties.description: Rendered fats of animals other than pigs, excluding tallow oil or stearine.

properties.label: Tallowtree seed
properties.description: Borneo tallow tree (Shorea aptera; S. stenocarpa); Chinese tallow tree (Sapium sebiferum; Stillingia sebifera). Grown wild and cultivated. FAO considers vegetable tallow and stillingia oil to be primary products (see below).

properties.label: Tangerines, mandarins, clementines, satsumas
properties.description: Mandarin, tangerine (Citrus reticulata); clementine, satsuma (C. unshiu).

properties.label: Tapioca, cassava
properties.description: See 121. Obtained from cassava starch and used in the preparation of puddings and in infant foods.

properties.label: Tapioca, potatoes
properties.description: A product obtained by heating potato starch mixed with water. Tapioca may be in the form of flakes, grains, pearls, siftings, seeds or other similar forms. Used in the preparation of soups and puddings or in foods for invalids.

properties.label: Taro (cocoyam)
properties.description: Dasheen, eddoe, taro, old cocoyam(Colocasia esculenta). Aroids cultivated for their edible starchy corms or underground stems. Taro is grown throughout the tropics for food. Trade data cover both fresh and dried taro.

properties.label: Tea
properties.description: Camellia sinensis; Thea sinensis; Thea assaamica. Includes green tea (unfermented), black tea (fermented), and partially fermented tea. Excludes green tea eaten as a vegetable.

properties.label: Tea nes
properties.description: Various plants used for making infusions like tea, i.e. herbal teas.

properties.label: Tea, mate extracts
properties.description: Includes essences, concentrates and preparations of tea and matâ.

properties.label: Tobacco products nes
properties.description: Includes smoking, chewing, snuff tobacco, homogenized or compressed tobacco, manufactured tobacco substitutes, tobacco extracts and essences.

properties.label: Tobacco, unmanufactured
properties.description: Nicotiana tabacum. Unmanufactured dry tobacco, including refuse that is not stemmed or stripped, or is partly or wholly stemmed or stripped.

properties.label: Tomatoes
properties.description: Lycopersicon esculentum.

properties.label: Tomatoes, paste
properties.description: Tomatoes prepared or preserved o/t by vinegar, in the form of paste, purâe or concentrate. Includes juice of dry weight content of 7% or more.

properties.label: Tomatoes, peeled
properties.description: Prepared or preserved o/t by vinegar; either whole or in pieces.

properties.label: Triticale
properties.description: A minor cereal that is a cross between wheat and rye, combining the quality and yield of wheat with the hardiness of rye.

properties.label: Tung nuts
properties.description: Aleurites cordata; A. fordii. Valued mainly for their oil.

properties.label: Turkeys
properties.description: Meleagris gallopavo. See 1057.

properties.label: Turnips for fodder
properties.description: Brassica rapa var. rapifera. Especially cultivated for fodder.

properties.label: Vanilla
properties.description: Vanilla planifolia; V. pompona. The fruit (or bean) of a climbing plant of the orchid family. Includes whole, crushed or ground.

properties.label: Vegetable tallow
properties.description: Obtained by pressure extraction or by solvent from the kernels of the fruit of the Borneo tallow tree and from the outer coating that surrounds the seeds of the fruit of the Chinese tallow tree. Used as a substitute for cocoa butter. Also used in soap, candles, medicines and cosmetics.

properties.label: Vegetables and roots fodder
properties.description: Any other crop of the vegetable group that is cultivated for fodder.

properties.label: Vegetables in vinegar
properties.description: Vegetables, fruit, nuts and other edible parts of plants, prepared or preserved with vinegar or acetic acid, with or without added sugar, salt, spices, etc. Includes pickles.

properties.label: Vegetables, dehydrated
properties.description: Vegetables that are dried, dehydrated, evaporated or freeze-dried. Includes dried vegetables that are broken or powdered.

properties.label: Vegetables, fresh nes
properties.description: Including inter alia: bamboo shoots (Bambusa spp.); beets, chards (Beta vulgaris); capers (Capparis spinosa); cardoons (Cynara cardunculus); celery (Apium graveolens); chervil (Anthriscus cerefolium); cress (Lepidium sativum); fennel (Foeniculum vulgare); horseradish (Cochlearia armoracia); marjoram, sweet (Majorana hortensis); oyster plant (Tragopogon porrifolius); parsley (Petroselinum crispum); parsnips (Pastinaca sativa); radish (Raphanus sativus); rhubarb (Rheum spp.); rutabagas, swedes (Brassica napus); savory (Satureja hortensis); scorzonera (Scorzonera hispanica); sorrel (Rumex acetosa); soybean sprouts tarragon (Artemisia dracunculus); watercress (Nasturtium officinale). Other vegetables that are not identified separately because of their minor relevance at the international level. Because of their limited local importance, some countries report vegetables under this heading that are classified individually by FAO.

items.label: Vegetables, fresh or dried products nes

properties.membername: Vegetables, fresh or dried products nes
properties.label: Vegetables, fresh or dried products nes
properties.description: Fruit stones, kernels and other vegetable products used primarily for human food that are not specified or included elsewhere.

properties.label: Vegetables, frozen
properties.description: Vegetables, either uncooked, or cooked by steaming or boiling in water, and then frozen.

properties.label: Vegetables, homogenized preparations
properties.description: Preparations Vegetables prepared for dietetic and infant food.

properties.label: Vegetables, leguminous nes
properties.description: Vicia faba. For shelling.

properties.label: Vegetables, preserved nes
properties.description: Vegetables prepared or preserved o/t by vinegar and which have not been frozen.

properties.label: Vegetables, preserved, frozen
properties.description: Vegetables that are prepared or preserved o/t by vinegar, and then frozen.

properties.label: Vegetables, temporarily preserved
properties.description: Vegetables preserved with SO2, brine, etc., but which are unsuitable for consumption in that state.

properties.label: Vermouths & similar
properties.description: Beverages made with wine of fresh grapes and flavoured with aromatic substances.

properties.label: Vetches
properties.description: Spring/common vetch (Vicia sativa). Used mainly for animal feed.

properties.label: Wafers
properties.description: Communion wafers, empty cachets for pharmaceutical use and sealing wafers.

properties.label: Walnuts, shelled
properties.description: Around 53% of the weight in shell.

properties.label: Walnuts, with shell
properties.description: Jugland spp.: J. regia. Produced in temperate zones of the Northern Hemisphere, particularly in the United States.

properties.label: Watermelons
properties.description: Citrullus vulgaris.

properties.label: Waters,ice etc
properties.description: Includes natural or artificial mineral waters without added sugar, sweeteners or flavourings.

properties.label: Waxes vegetable
properties.description: Including inter alia: candelilla (Euphorbia antisyphilitica; Pedilanthus pavonis); carnauba (Copernicia cerifera); urucury (Attalea excelsa); palm wax (Ceroxylon andicolum). Vegetable waxes, whether crude or refined, bleached or coloured. Excludes mixtures and chemically modified waxes.

properties.label: Wheat
properties.description: Triticum spp.: common (T. aestivum) durum (T. durum) spelt (T. spelta). Common and durum wheat are the main types. Among common wheat, the main varieties are spring and winter, hard and soft, and red and white. At the national level, different varieties should be reported separately, reflecting their different uses. Used mainly for human food.

properties.label: Whey, condensed
properties.description: Whey paste.

properties.label: Whey, dry
properties.description: Used in both food and animal feed.

properties.label: Whey, fresh
properties.description: The liquid part of the milk that remains after the separation of curd in cheese making. Its main food use is in the preparation of whey cheese, whey drinks and fermented whey drinks. The main industrial uses are in the manufacture of lactose, whey paste and dried whey.

properties.label: Wine
properties.description: Wines of fresh grapes of all qualities, including sparkling, fortified and dessert wines.

properties.label: Wool, degreased
properties.description: Includes scoured and carbonized, but does not include carded or combed wool.

properties.label: Wool, greasy
properties.description: A natural fibre taken from sheep or lambs. Includes fleece-washed, shorn and pulled wool (from slaughtered animals), but does not include carded or combed wool.

properties.label: Wool, hair waste
properties.description: Noils of wool or animal hair not garnetted; other waste of wool and animal hair (excluding horsehair) not covered in 1007.

properties.label: Wool, shoddy
properties.description: Garnetted stock of wool or of fine or coarse animal hair obtained by garnetting rags or waste of spinning, weaving, knitting etc.

properties.label: Wool, tops
properties.description: Slivers consisting of long fibres laid parallel by combing and then wound into balls.

properties.label: Yams
properties.description: Dioscorea spp.. The principal edible yams are widely grown throughout the tropics. A starchy staple foodstuff, normally eaten as a vegetable, boiled, baked or fried. In West Africa they are consumed mainly as "fufu", a stiff glutinous dough. Trade data cover both fresh and dried yams.

properties.label: Yautia (cocoyam)
properties.description: Xanthosoma spp.; malanga, new cocoyam, ocumo, tannia (X. sagittifolium). Several plants are included in this group, some with edible tubers and others with edible stems (also called aroids). Yautia is grown mainly in the Caribbean and is used for food. Trade data cover both fresh and dried yautia.

properties.label: Yoghurt
properties.description: A fermented milk food.

properties.label: Yoghurt, concentrated or not
properties.description: Includes additives such as sugar, flavouring materials, fruit or cocoa.
